<h4 id="Business">Business Travelers</h4>
<br/>
<b>Performance</b>
<p>The standard performance requirement for a traveling businessman can be somewhat
    variable, depending on the type of business to be performed.  If you are using high-end performance 
    software for your business, then of course, you will need a faster processor such as the Intel Core i7, lots
of RAM, and preferably good memory.  On the contrary, if you are going to be doing light web surfing
or emailing, then you can  settle for a lower performance dual core processor.</p>
<br/>
<b>Portability</b>
<p>This may be obvious, but a business traveler will most definitely require a portable laptop.
The laptop display should be no larger than 15 inches to ensure portability.  Laptops with
long battery life, say, at least 4.5 hours, will also be quite useful during travel where external
power is not supplied.  In considering the battery size, you don't want one that is too large, such as a 9 cell lithium ion,
because it doesn't allow for much portability (it sticks out the back of your computer), but if you choose
a smaller size, such as the 6 cell lithium ion, then your laptop will be more portable but its battery life won't be as lenghty.  This is
a trade-off that the businessman has to decide on.</p>
<br/>
<b>Features</b>
<p>For most businessmen, Microsoft Office is essential, so be sure to get one that comes with it
or you can buy it yourself.  Also, it's still quite unfortunate that most laptops today are still made of
plastic, even though Aluminum laptops are a much better alternative, given that they are durable, usually scratch resistant, 
and won't break as you carry it around.</p>
<br/>
<p>Having said all of this, the <a href="../laptops/lenovo">Lenovo Thinkpads</a> are a great option and are particularly built with
the businessman in mind.</p>
